hildren’s development.Parental Incarceration and the Family brings a family perspective to our understanding of what it means to have so many of our nation’s parents in prison. Drawing from the field’s most recent research and the author’s own fieldwork, Joyce Arditti offers an in-depth look at how incarceration affects entire families: offender parents, children, and care-givers. Through the use of exemplars, anecdotes, and reflections, Joyce Arditti puts a human face on the mass of humanity behind bars, as well as those family members who are affected by a parent’s imprisonment. In focusing on offenders as parents, a radically different social policy agenda emerges-one that calls for real reform and that responds to the collective vulnerabilities of the incarcerated and their kin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren of prisonersxUnited States. 0aChildren of prisonerszUnited States. 0aChildren of women prisonersxUnited States. 0aChildren of women prisonerszUnited States. 0aPrisonersxFamily relationshipsxUnited States. 0aPrisonersxFamily relationshipszUnited States. 0aPrisoners' familiesxUnited States. 0aPrisoners' familieszUnited States. 0aWomen prisonersxFamily relationshipsxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aWomen prisonersxFamily relationshipszUnited States. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Psychotherapy / Couples & Family.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814708057.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814708057423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814708057/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles